node.text:
In a portfolio shared across 27 editions of Vogue around the world, 19 models flaunt 35 looks from the fall collections; their styles ranging from the smartly subdued to the go-for-broke glamorous. Representing both the U.S. and the U.K., fashion editors Camilla Nickerson, @Alex_Jordan_Harrington, Poppy Kain, and Julia Sarr-Jamois led the effort, thinking along four broad aesthetic lines: the short and bright, inventive approaches to leather, reimagined florals, and bold spins on knitwear. Click the link in our bio to take in the joyous results.
Photographed by @Studio_Jackson and styled by @Alex_Jordan_Harrington, @PoppyKain, Camilla Nickerson and @SarrJamois, Vogue, September 2021.

node.text: @sakspotts showed its fall 2021 collection the yard of the home Arne Jacobsen, the Functionalist Danish architect and inventor of the Egg chair, built for himself around 1930. The Bauhaus-style house he designed for himself is a clean-lined, white-painted, minimal box. It was here that Cathrine Saks and Barbara Potts revealed their collection and their new direction. See more at the link in bio. Video by @styledumonde

node.text: A slice of the Big Apple is coming to Copenhagen, served up in the form of a monographic exhibition, “My Paper World,” featuring the work of @phoebenewyork at the Horsens Art Museum. Read more at the link in bio.

node.text: @jonathancohenstudio hasn’t wasted a scrap of fabric in years. From entire rolls of leftover silk to the tiny bits left on the factory floor, it all gets repurposed into pillows, patchwork dresses, scrunchies, face masks, and totes as part of his upcycled Studio Collection. Today, he’s adding an exciting new category to the list: jewelry. We got a glimpse of the fabric-wrapped beaded necklaces in his fall 2021 collection: In some looks, stacks of them were layered around the neck, while others featured extra-long strands looped over the torso like harnesses. Cohen partnered with the women of @refugeesarts to produce the limited capsule for his website. “During the pandemic, it became more important to me than ever to support handicrafts and artisans,” Cohen says. “It’s the reason why organizations such as Nest and RAI are so important; they create [connections] to the artisans when you can’t travel. This is essential and creates beautiful results.” Tap the link in bio to read the full story and shop the necklaces.
